[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'WhisperFlow or Hex, which is the free open-source alternative, which will allow you to talk instead of typing, which is like 10 times faster. Step two is identify your board members. Once Claude knows what you want to accomplish in the next 1, 5, 10 years, ask it to'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'suggest who should be on your board. For this video, we\'re going to start with two people, but you can add as many as you want. Generally, I like to bias towards people who have publicly available information, for example, YouTube creators, because their full body of work is accessible, and that'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'serves as training data as you recreate these people on your board. And for any prompt that I go through, just take a screenshot of it and then send it into Claude essentially the same as typing. So, after you know who\'s on your board, step three is ingest their content to'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create their clone. So, go to YouTube or wherever that person has training data available and pull all the links to the content that you want to ingest. Then, paste that right into Claude and ask Claude to ingest that data into your project. Here, you can see a prompt I'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use, which helps me ingest specifically YouTube data. Step four is create your board skill. Once steps one and three are done, create a custom skill that lets you ask your board questions in one go. We\'ll go deeper on the concept of custom skills in project four, but the'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quick version is that a skill lets you run a multi-step process automatically by just calling that specific skill. If I had to really simplify it, just think of it as a reusable prompt that you can easily update. In this case, we\'re going'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to call the skill ask the board, so Claude knows to loop through every single board member instead of just one, and then gets you a response based on all of their analysis. Step five, now that you\'ve created the skill, you can actually go ahead and ask your question.'

[01:51] [scene:talk]
